      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>Larchmont residents hoping to expand their homes into ''McMansions'' will have to wait.</p>
        <p>The village Board of Trustees voted last month to enact a six-month moratorium on zoning variances. The action will restrict residents from extending their homes close to property boundaries and from increasing total house size beyond current zoning laws.</p>
        <p>The village will also hire a consultant to study the impact of larger homes on the community during the six-month ''breathing period,'' said Ken Bialo, the village mayor.</p>
        <p>''When someone builds a large house on a small lot, it affects the atmosphere, lighting and privacy of neighboring houses,'' Mr. Bialo said. ''We don't want elephants on a block of rabbits.''</p>
        <p>Larchmont is the latest community to address the growing size of houses in Westchester. Mamaroneck village already has a law, as do Scarsdale and Eastchester.</p>
        <p>William S. Beaver</p>
        <p>IN BUSINESS</p>
      </block>
